Writer(s): John Paul Jones, John Bonham, Robert Plant, James Page
This song is the opening track on the album. When is was released as a single in the USA it became the band's first hit single and was eventually certified Gold.
The lyrics for this song were borrowed by Robert Plant from the song "You Need Loving" by Small Faces, which, in turn, was a cover of Muddy Waters' song "You Need Love". The lyrics were originally written by Willie Dixon. The Small Faces were never sued by Dixon, but Led Zeppelin was in 1985. Plant confessed the fact and said, "...well, you only get caught when you're successful. That's the game."
The distinct drum sound of this song was recorded in the big room at Olympic Studios in London, which had 28-foot ceilings. The drum kit was on a platform and microphones were put and hung in different places at different heights.
The freeform section in the middle of this song was produced by Jimmy Page and engineer Eddie Kramer by "twiddling every knob known to man" on a console.
There is a shorter version of this song lasting 3:10 (instead of the album's version 5:33) released by Atlantic Records for the promotion on radio stations. It doesn't have the freeform section in the middle and fades out earlier. This version wasn't intended for commercial release, but some copies were sold in the USA anyway, and they are collectors items now.

Thanks to David (Dagrah) Graham RE/SE, Steve Johnson, Roxana Horga for correcting these lyrics.
Writer(s): Jimmy Page, Robert Plant
This song was the first band's song for which Robert Plant wrote all the lyrics. He dedicated the song to his wife.
The lyrics "if the sun refused to shine" and "when mountains crumble to the sea" were taken from a Jimi Hendrix song "If 6 was 9".
Record producer Rick Rubin has noted this song's structure saying, "The delicacy of the vocals is incredible; the acoustic guitar and the organ work together to create an otherworldly presence."
Led Zeppelin was a big influence for Tori Amos, so that she made a cover of this song on the extended versions of her "Crucify" single.
This song was recorded by Jimmy Page and Robert Plant for their "No Quarter: Jimmy Page and Robert Plant Unledded" album in 1994.

Jimmy Page's guitar solo on this song inspired Eddie Van Halen to create his "tapping" technique.
This song was recorded at A&R Recording and Atlantic Studios in New York City during the band's second tour in the USA.
Many of the band live shows in 1971 and 1972 began with "Immigrant Song" segued right into "Heartbreaker".

Thanks to Matt, Roger Daltry for correcting these lyrics.
Writer(s): James Jon, Page Jimmy
This song is the opening track of the album. It is about the Viking invasions.
The lyrics of this song were influenced by the band's visit to Iceland where they performed on a concert in ReykjavÃ­k. Robert Plant said, "We did come from the land of the ice and snow... The university prepared a concert hall for us and it was phenomenal. The response from the kids was remarkable and we had a great time. 'Immigrant Song' was about that trip..."
The line "the hammer of the gods" from this song's lyrics gave the name to the book "Hammer of the Gods: The Led Zeppelin Saga" by author Stephen Davis.
Jack Black (Tenacious D) begged for permission from the band to use this song in the film "School Of Rock" where he played the main character. He said on the DVD, "It may seem corny, but it worked. The moral of the story is don't be too proud to beg."
This song is prominently featured in the film "Thor: Ragnarok" (2017).

Writer(s): J. Page, J.p. Jones, R. Plant
This song's title is a reference to a nameless strayed black retriever that ran around the Headley Grange (a mansion in Hampshire, England) during recording of the album. The retriever was old but still sexually active like the main character of the song, who has a desperate love desire.
For this song John Paul Jones wanted to use a winding riff and unusual rhythm changes that people could not dance to. Jones wrote the song's basic riff on the back of a train ticket on his way to a rehearsal at Jimmy Page's Pangbourne boathouse in 1968. The drums and guitar actually play completely different patterns.
A capella verses of this song were inspired by Fleetwood Mac's song "Oh Well". Jimmy Page performed "Oh Well" with The Black Crowes on their 1999 tour.
John Paul Jones wanted to try Electric Blues on this song. He got that idea after hearing Muddy Waters' album "Electric Mud" (1968). As a result "Black Dog" was an example of the blues-rock track on the album.

Jimmy Page said that the basis of this song was created during a jam session, whilst the band were trying to finish the track "Four Sticks". After one of the failed takes John Bonham began to play the drum sequence based on the Little Richard's song "Keep A-Knockin'", and Page added a guitar riff, the most part of which is heard on the song.
The song is one of the best-known songs in the band's repertoire. Robert Plant wrote the lyrics in response to critics who claimed that their previous album "Led Zeppelin III" wasn't really rock 'n' roll.
"The Book of Love", mentioned in this song, was a popular song by The Monotones.

Writer(s): Page James Patrick, Plant R A
"Stairway To Heaven", released in November 1971 on the band's 4th album, is often rated among the greatest rock songs of all time. However, it wasn't a chart hit because it was never released as a single.
Robert Plant's own explanation of the lyrics was that it "was some cynical aside about a woman getting everything she wanted all the time without giving back any thought or consideration."
Jimmy Page says that "'Stairway' crystallized the essence of the band. It had everything there and showed the band at its best... as a band, as a unit. Not talking about solos or anything, it had everything there. It was a milestone for us. Every musician wants to do something of lasting quality, something which will hold up for a long time and I guess we did it with this song."
In 1982, televangelist Paul Crouch declared that, when played backward, the "If there's a bustle in your hedgerow, don't be alarmed now..." segment says this: "Here's to my sweet Satan / The one whose little path would make me sad, whose power is Satan / He will give those with him 666 / There was a little toolshed where he made us suffer, sad Satan." Although that part of the song when played backwards does sound somewhat similar to Crouch's interpretation, it's just a bizarre coincidence. "Who on Earth would have ever thought of doing that?" Robert Plant said of the Satanism charges. "You've got to have a lot of time on your hands to even consider that people would do that."

Writer(s): Page James Patrick, Plant R A, Bonham John
This song was inspired by a drive through the Sahara Desert in Morocco when the band was heading to the National Festival of folklore in 1973. Robert Plant, who penned the majority of lyrics, explained, The whole inspiration came from the fact that the road went on and on and on. ...and there was seemingly no end to it."
This song's unique guitar riff is one of the most memorable guitar riffs in rock history. It was developed by Jimmy Page over the course of two years. The song's composition was inspired by Middle-Eastern, Moroccan, and Indian music.
At the time this song was composed, none of the band members had ever been to Kashmir.
Robert Plant once said, "One of my favourite Zeppelin tracks because it possessed all the latent energy and power that wasn't heavy metal. It was something else. It was the pride of Led Zeppelin."
Jimmy Page and Robert Plant recorded a live 12-minute version of this song with a Moroccan/Egyptian orchestra for their album "No Quarter" in 1994.
